00:19:28.283 --> 00:19:32.580
Cyert, Cohon, those are but a few.

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:38.290
Each of these presidents and others of
this storied institution led through

00:19:38.290 --> 00:19:43.110
myriad chapters of American history,
world history, the turn of the century,

00:19:43.110 --> 00:19:47.080
the Great Depression, the explosion of
technology that Jim was talking about just

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:53.450
a few minutes ago,
civil unrest, war and peace.

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:56.970
And throughout all of this,
presidents of Carnegie Mellon

00:19:56.970 --> 00:20:00.900
have guided this institution to
the forefront of educational excellence

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:04.710
and they have shaped the minds of so
many young people.

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:11.110
All the while ensuring that the university
remained a source of inspiration,

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:14.100
a guiding light, a beacon of hope.

00:20:15.170 --> 00:20:18.940
And now we pass this
torch to Farnam Jahanian.

00:20:20.580 --> 00:20:24.070
There is no one who is better suited
to lead us into the next chapter

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:26.590
and this next chapter is
arguably the most important ever.

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:30.208
For we do live in very,
very interesting times.

00:20:30.208 --> 00:20:33.750
We have seen, and
this is just the beginning,

00:20:33.750 --> 00:20:36.770
but we have seen incredible
advances in technology.

