On behalf of the Carnegie Mellon
University community.  This token is meant

00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:35.630
to serve as a reminder of the attributes
within the CMU community that thistles

00:41:35.630 --> 00:41:42.690
are said to embody- strength,
bravery, determination, and devotion.

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:46.590
The first characteristic is strength.

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:49.060
Our strength is in the work we do and

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:54.220
in our approach to it that is
equal parts fearless and curious.

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:57.920
This strength lives in our students,
our faculty,

00:41:57.920 --> 00:42:03.490
our staff, our alumni, our leadership
and our board of trustees.

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:06.238
All of our hearts are in the work.

00:42:16.498 --> 00:42:20.950
&gt;&gt; The second characteristic is bravery,
we've got it.

00:42:20.950 --> 00:42:25.690
The people who are drawn the Carnegie
Mellon view challenges not as obstacles

00:42:25.690 --> 00:42:27.770
but as opportunities.

00:42:27.770 --> 00:42:33.444
We inspire each other to dig in,
dive deeper, peel back the extra layer,

00:42:33.444 --> 00:42:38.856
continually in search of breakthroughs
that will make a difference.

00:42:46.407 --> 00:42:48.510
&gt;&gt; The next characteristic
is determination.

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:53.610
We are determined to solve the most
difficult questions posed by society.

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:59.640
In order to do so we use self motivation,
discipline, and multiple

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:04.379
opportunities to explore potential
solutions that no one has posed yet.

00:43:13.938 --> 00:43:16.600
&gt;&gt; The final characteristic is devotion.

00:43:16.600 --> 00:43:18.620
We are devoted to Carnegie Mellon.

00:43:18.620 --> 00:43:22.350
We're devoted to its experimentation,
its rigour and

00:43:22.350 --> 00:43:27.100
research with the human dimension
of purpose and tangible impact.

00:43:27.100 --> 00:43:31.534
That impact is felt on campus in
Pittsburgh, throughout the nation and

00:43:31.534 --> 00:43:32.789
across the globe.

00:43:38.698 --> 00:43:41.165
&gt;&gt; President Jahanian,
can you please join us?

00:43:43.930 --> 00:43:48.154
We hope this sculpture reminds you of
these characteristics interwoven in

00:43:48.154 --> 00:43:50.576
the CMU community, and your leadership.

00:43:50.576 --> 00:43:56.278
May it inspire you everyday, let it
forever commemorate and symbolize this

00:43:56.278 --> 00:44:02.083
day as we move forward into the future
we are committed to creating together.

00:44:02.083 --> 00:44:12.083
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:44:38.960 --> 00:44:42.925
&gt;&gt; What a beautiful representation
of all that is Carnegie Mellon.

00:44:42.925 --> 00:44:46.090
Thank you so much for
sharing this beautiful community gift

00:44:46.090 --> 00:44:48.260
on behalf of everyone at CMU, thank you.

00:44:50.710 --> 00:44:54.640
The investiture of a president
is held as an academic ceremony

00:44:54.640 --> 00:44:56.500
much like commencement and,

00:44:56.500 --> 00:45:02.180
like graduation, it symbolizes an important
transition, a right of passage.

00:45:02.180 --> 00:45:05.310
Today's ceremony is a right
of passage not only for Dr.

00:45:05.310 --> 00:45:07.900
Jahanian, but also for Carnegie Mellon.

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:14.010
New leadership can inspire new thinking,
new directions and new aspirations

00:45:14.010 --> 00:45:17.898
and I'm confident that under Dr.
Jahanian presidency,

00:45:17.898 --> 00:45:22.910
university will take on a fresh group
of challenges and ask new questions.

00:45:24.110 --> 00:45:28.651
Dr. Jahanian and Faculty Marshals,
will you please come forward to join me?

00:45:46.505 --> 00:45:50.269
Farnam Jahanian, by the authority
of the Board of Trustees and

00:45:50.269 --> 00:45:54.993
with the enthusiastic approval of
the faculty, staff, students, alumni, and

00:45:54.993 --> 00:45:56.842
this distinguished assembly,

00:45:56.842 --> 00:46:01.032
I present into your keeping the charter
of Carnegie Mellon university.

00:46:03.034 --> 00:46:13.034
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:46:14.318 --> 00:46:19.073
&gt;&gt; And I also present to you the great
seal of the university, the symbol of

00:46:19.073 --> 00:46:23.751
the high office you now hold, and
invest you with all of the rights,

00:46:23.751 --> 00:46:28.368
privileges, and responsibilities
of the Office of the President.

00:46:28.368 --> 00:46:37.096
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:46:39.841 --> 00:46:49.841
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:04.187 --> 00:47:05.627
&gt;&gt; Ladies and gentlemen,

00:47:05.627 --> 00:47:10.379
on behalf of the board of trustees and
the members of the academy, I now present

00:47:10.379 --> 00:47:15.214
you with the 10th president of
Carnegie University, Dr. Farnam Jahanian.

00:47:15.214 --> 00:47:35.360
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:37.120
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:47:37.120 --> 00:47:41.360
&gt;&gt;[APPLAUSE]

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:43.360
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:47:44.080 --> 00:47:45.920
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:47:46.400 --> 00:47:54.880
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:47:56.560 --> 00:48:01.012
&gt;&gt; Wow, Chairman Rohr,

00:48:01.012 --> 00:48:06.167
trustees, faculty colleagues,

00:48:06.167 --> 00:48:10.591
students, staff, alumni, and

00:48:10.591 --> 00:48:16.761
honored guests,
good morning and thank you.

00:48:20.283 --> 00:48:25.314
It's a great honor and
a truly humbling experience to stand

00:48:25.314 --> 00:48:30.460
here as the tenth president of
Carnegie Mellon University.

00:48:32.080 --> 00:48:37.360
I hereby accept the symbols,
the Office of the President, and

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:42.520
all of the responsibility
pertaining thereto.

00:48:42.520 --> 00:48:53.060
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:55.978
&gt;&gt; It brings me great joy to celebrate

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:58.800
this occasion with my family,
especially my wife,

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:05.175
Tris and my children,
Daniel, Thomas, and Sarah.

00:49:05.175 --> 00:49:10.690
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Who

00:49:10.690 --> 00:49:13.700
have always been my greatest blessing.

00:49:15.530 --> 00:49:20.808
I am so touched by the presence of
friends, former students, colleagues

00:49:20.808 --> 00:49:26.015
and collaborators, who have traveled
from across the country to be here.

00:49:26.015 --> 00:49:30.116
I also wanna acknowledge
community partners and

00:49:30.116 --> 00:49:33.817
civic leaders from the Pittsburgh region,

00:49:33.817 --> 00:49:39.838
who are showing their support for
this university today and every day

00:49:39.838 --> 00:49:44.523
and I would especially like
to thank my dear friends,

00:49:44.523 --> 00:49:49.417
Marlene Behrmann, Keith Block,
and Martha Pollack,

00:49:49.417 --> 00:49:53.910
for their kind and
thoughtful words this morning.

00:49:55.670 --> 00:49:58.555
Martha, I've been
following your footsteps.

00:49:58.555 --> 00:50:02.550
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; What you didn't tell them is that you

00:50:02.550 --> 00:50:07.879
were my department head and my provost,
my boss for many, many years.

00:50:07.879 --> 00:50:09.430
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; I

00:50:09.430 --> 00:50:10.990
don't know what you're
planning to do next.

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:14.042
I'm pretty happy to be here,
so don't do anything else.

00:50:14.042 --> 00:50:18.314
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]

00:50:18.314 --> 00:50:25.175
&gt;&gt;[APPLAUSE]

00:50:25.175 --> 00:50:28.753
&gt;&gt; Today's ceremony is a celebration

00:50:28.753 --> 00:50:34.835
steeped in tradition,
the singing of our national anthem,

00:50:34.835 --> 00:50:40.335
our academic regalia,
the iconic sound of bagpipes.

00:50:42.485 --> 00:50:45.691
These rituals remind us that this moment

00:50:45.691 --> 00:50:50.440
iss not about the beginning
of my journey as President.

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:55.535
Rather, this ceremony celebrates
our storied history as a community

00:50:55.535 --> 00:50:59.865
of scholars in a nation driven
by learning and discovery.

00:50:59.865 --> 00:51:04.880
CMU is, relatively, a young university.

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:10.260
We've come so far in such a short time,
and our accomplishments

00:51:10.260 --> 00:51:14.899
would have not been possible without
the leadership of my predecessors.

00:51:16.540 --> 00:51:19.620
I especially want to acknowledge and

00:51:19.620 --> 00:51:24.465
thank President Emeritus Jerry Cohon

00:51:24.465 --> 00:51:32.232
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt;aAnd past Provost Mark Kamlet

00:51:32.232 --> 00:51:37.150
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; for their

00:51:37.150 --> 00:51:41.963
enduring commitment

00:51:41.963 --> 00:51:47.100
to this university.

00:51:47.100 --> 00:51:50.820
We are so grateful to you for
everything you have done for

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:52.495
Carnegie Mellon, Mark and Jerry.

00:51:52.495 --> 00:51:59.960
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Of course,

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:03.760
great leaders are inspired by
an extraordinary community.

00:52:03.760 --> 00:52:07.780
As Mark and Jerry can attest,
countless faculty, staff, alumni

00:52:07.780 --> 00:52:12.770
and partners help to build the foundation
of excellence CMU enjoys today.

00:52:14.070 --> 00:52:17.911
I am grateful to all the men and
women who have guided this

00:52:17.911 --> 00:52:22.430
university since its founding,
and who will secure its future.

00:52:23.730 --> 00:52:27.295
In particular,
I wish to recognize the members of

00:52:27.295 --> 00:52:32.140
Carnegie Mellon's Board of Trustees,
who are the stewards of this institution.

00:52:32.140 --> 00:52:37.140
I am so grateful for
their trust they have placed in me.

00:52:37.140 --> 00:52:41.655
Trustees, would you please stand to be
recognized, Carnegie Mellon trustees.

00:52:41.655 --> 00:52:51.766
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:52:51.766 --> 00:52:52.410
&gt;&gt; Thank you, please be seated.

00:52:52.410 --> 00:52:58.242
I would also like to acknowledge and
thank the university deans,

00:52:58.242 --> 00:53:02.591
vice provost, and
executive management team,

00:53:02.591 --> 00:53:09.180
my co-conspirators, who do so
much to advance CMU every day.

00:53:09.180 --> 00:53:12.455
Would the university leadership
team please stand to be recognized.

00:53:12.455 --> 00:53:22.455
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:53:25.236 --> 00:53:30.000
&gt;&gt; Like many of us here, I left home
as a teenager to pursue an education.

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:35.161
As I prepared for
my journey from Iran to Texas,

00:53:35.161 --> 00:53:38.332
I remember asking my
mother to help me pack.

00:53:38.332 --> 00:53:44.086
She said,
pack light because what ever you need,

00:53:44.086 --> 00:53:48.744
you will find there. Pack light because

00:53:48.744 --> 00:53:53.548
what ever you need, you will find there.

00:53:53.548 --> 00:53:58.610
And so as I left home with
little more than a sense

00:53:58.610 --> 00:54:03.410
of optimism and a desire to
make the most of the incredible

00:54:03.410 --> 00:54:08.930
opportunities that only an education
in the United States could provide,

00:54:10.020 --> 00:54:13.820
I've carried my mother's words
with me over these many years.

00:54:15.190 --> 00:54:20.664
I think her advice may have been based
on a hope that I would return home

00:54:20.664 --> 00:54:26.220
once the initial excitement wore off,
but I was pretty stubborn.

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:31.970
In fact, I got my tenacity from her,

00:54:31.970 --> 00:54:37.060
along with a work ethic
instilled in me by my father.

00:54:37.060 --> 00:54:38.820
My siblings who are here
can attest to that.

00:54:40.810 --> 00:54:44.090
But looking back, perhaps my mother
was hinting at the knowledge

00:54:44.090 --> 00:54:46.210
I would accumulate in the journey ahead.

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:49.330
As a teacher and advisor,

00:54:49.330 --> 00:54:54.290
I came to understand the incredible
power of education to change lives.

00:54:54.290 --> 00:54:58.800
As a researcher, mentor, entrepreneur,
I observed the potential of

00:54:58.800 --> 00:55:04.140
a single idea to launch a new enterprise
or disrupt an entire industry

00:55:05.800 --> 00:55:09.870
and during my time in public
service in Washington,

00:55:09.870 --> 00:55:14.676
DC, I saw how these ideas,
how the ideas emerging from higher

00:55:14.676 --> 00:55:21.200
education serve as a foundation
of our success as a nation.

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:24.780
My 30-year career ultimately led me here,

00:55:24.780 --> 00:55:28.856
to this city and this university.

00:55:28.856 --> 00:55:34.810
This community, our community

00:55:34.810 --> 00:55:41.350
embodies all of my most fervent
beliefs and my greatest passions.

00:55:41.350 --> 00:55:44.950
Every day at CMU, I am inspired by you.

00:55:46.390 --> 00:55:50.680
Here, the world's most ambitious
students collaborate at the edges and

00:55:50.680 --> 00:55:55.430
intersection of diverse fields, and
go on to change the world as alumni.

00:55:56.530 --> 00:56:02.260
Here, faculty leave an indelible mark
on society through their scholarship.

00:56:03.541 --> 00:56:05.241
Here, professionals and

00:56:05.241 --> 00:56:10.040
dedicated staff create an environment
that supports our shared success.

00:56:11.950 --> 00:56:19.160
These are the people and the ideals that
set CMU apart from the very beginning.

00:56:19.160 --> 00:56:26.935
When Andrew Carnegie founded the Carnegie Technical Schools to educate the sons and

00:56:26.935 --> 00:56:30.996
daughters of factory workers in 1900.

00:56:30.996 --> 00:56:32.410
Early, it's an evolution.

00:56:33.490 --> 00:56:38.040
This institution would house two
great learning environments,

00:56:38.040 --> 00:56:41.160
the College of Engineering and
the College of Fine Arts.

00:56:42.190 --> 00:56:49.720
You see right from the start, we were
bringing together creativity and industry.

00:56:50.800 --> 00:56:55.390
Our willingness to take risks
continued in the 20th century when

00:56:55.390 --> 00:57:00.320
we became the first degree granting
drama institution in the United States.

00:57:01.820 --> 00:57:06.987
And then when the Mellon Institute
of Research founded by Richard and

00:57:06.987 --> 00:57:13.237
Andrew Mellon, merged with Carnegie Tech
to create Carnegie Mellon University.

00:57:13.237 --> 00:57:17.394
And again, when Newell,
Simon, Perliss and

00:57:17.394 --> 00:57:22.886
Raj Reddy came to dominate
the emerging field of computer science

00:57:22.886 --> 00:57:28.120
and establish artificial intelligence
as the next frontier in human progress.

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:33.580
To paraphrase CS pioneer Grace Hopper,
the most

00:57:33.580 --> 00:57:38.540
dangerous phrase in the English language
is we've always done it this way.

00:57:40.680 --> 00:57:43.810
So at a time when computers
were barely understood.

00:57:45.150 --> 00:57:49.060
We were among the very first to
recognize the power of computing and

00:57:49.060 --> 00:57:51.870
we made some big bets.

00:57:51.870 --> 00:57:56.077
In 1965, we established our
Department of Computer Science,

00:57:56.077 --> 00:58:00.897
in 1979, we founded the first
Robotics Institute at the US University.

00:58:00.897 --> 00:58:04.414
In 1984, we attracted funding
from the federal government to

00:58:04.414 --> 00:58:07.170
launch the Software Engineering Institute.

00:58:07.170 --> 00:58:11.530
And in 1988, we announced the first

00:58:11.530 --> 00:58:15.570
college in the world devoted
solely to computer science.

00:58:16.950 --> 00:58:22.435
Ours is still the model
that others follow.

00:58:22.435 --> 00:58:32.420
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:33.960
&gt;&gt; In the process,

00:58:33.960 --> 00:58:38.550
we've created new fields of inquiry, such
as machine learning, transition design,

00:58:38.550 --> 00:58:40.489
and the science of learning.

00:58:41.560 --> 00:58:46.000
We've magnified our societal impact
through technologies like autonomous

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:48.710
vehicles and additive manufacturing.

00:58:49.840 --> 00:58:53.976
And we did all of this while
also cleaning up at the Tonys,

00:58:53.976 --> 00:58:57.241
the Emmys and
the Putnam competition.

00:58:57.241 --> 00:59:06.180
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; There's

00:59:06.180 --> 00:59:09.750
a lot to be gained by
looking back at our past.

00:59:09.750 --> 00:59:10.820
We see who we are,

00:59:12.540 --> 00:59:13.620
who we've always been.

00:59:14.870 --> 00:59:18.820
Alumni from those early years
would certainly see themselves

00:59:18.820 --> 00:59:20.820
in today's students.

00:59:20.820 --> 00:59:26.190
Entrepreneurial, creative, collaborative,

00:59:26.190 --> 00:59:30.672
whip smart, and just a little bit quirky.

00:59:30.672 --> 00:59:35.611
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; While the past has left a bright trail,

00:59:35.611 --> 00:59:39.923
the future is arriving faster than
anyone could have predicted and

00:59:39.923 --> 00:59:43.166
you've heard several
speakers talk about that.

00:59:43.166 --> 00:59:47.422
Our entire world is adapting
to unprecedented advances that

00:59:47.422 --> 00:59:52.170
are rapidly transforming our economy,
our society and our culture.

00:59:53.330 --> 01:00:00.100
We must ask ourselves, how can higher
education fit into this dazzling future?

01:00:01.400 --> 01:00:06.640
Indeed, our industry has
recently come under scrutiny.

01:00:06.640 --> 01:00:08.830
This is not a new phenomenon.

01:00:08.830 --> 01:00:13.636
Academic institutions have
often been seen as or

01:00:13.636 --> 01:00:17.170
criticized rather as ivory towers.

01:00:17.170 --> 01:00:21.307
But there is no doubt that sustained
investment in research and

01:00:21.307 --> 01:00:26.348
education has fueled our nation's
broad prosperity since World War II.

01:00:26.348 --> 01:00:35.799
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:00:35.799 --> 01:00:39.198
&gt;&gt; Universities exemplify our faith in

01:00:39.198 --> 01:00:46.003
the power of education to transcend
social economic and racial divides.

01:00:46.003 --> 01:00:50.132
To reinforce our role as
pillars of progressive society,

01:00:50.132 --> 01:00:55.106
higher education must approach our
mission with renewed attention to

01:00:55.106 --> 01:00:58.180
the unique demands of tomorrow.

01:00:58.180 --> 01:01:04.530
At stake is the ability of our society
to retain its fundamental commitment

01:01:04.530 --> 01:01:09.788
to democracy, truth, equity,
and freedom of expression.

01:01:09.788 --> 01:01:19.699
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:01:19.699 --> 01:01:21.103
&gt;&gt; At Carnegie Mellon,

01:01:21.103 --> 01:01:25.710
we have always responded to challenges
with trademark fearlessness.

01:01:26.840 --> 01:01:31.530
I'm reminded of the leadership
of Dick Cyert, who not only

01:01:31.530 --> 01:01:36.090
pioneered a new model for business
education as dean of our business school.

01:01:37.470 --> 01:01:42.470
But would later serve as one
the most visionary CMU presidents.

01:01:43.580 --> 01:01:47.170
More than 40 years ago, he made bold but

01:01:47.170 --> 01:01:51.780
calculated investments in the very
areas that define our leadership today.

01:01:53.160 --> 01:02:00.430
These risks were not always met with
broad support, but they paid off.

01:02:00.430 --> 01:02:05.570
As a result,
CMU grew from a small regional institution

01:02:05.570 --> 01:02:08.359
to an international center
of higher education.

01:02:09.660 --> 01:02:14.950
The time to be intentionally
bold is once again upon us.

01:02:14.950 --> 01:02:19.680
We have a singular opportunity to
wield our exceptional strength

01:02:20.810 --> 01:02:24.380
and make the next big investments
in our global leadership.

01:02:26.090 --> 01:02:30.890
Let's consider together what society
needs most from academic institutions In

01:02:30.890 --> 01:02:36.760
the context of our two core missions,
research and education.

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:41.990
At CMU, we advance human knowledge
through scholarly research and

01:02:41.990 --> 01:02:45.600
forge new connections to our
humanity through the arts.

01:02:46.850 --> 01:02:52.750
But the nature of research and creativity
is rapidly changing, increasingly becoming

01:02:52.750 --> 01:02:57.710
dependent on people working across
the boundaries of established disciplines

01:02:58.750 --> 01:03:02.270
and on computational
data-driven approaches

01:03:02.270 --> 01:03:05.210
that are accelerating discovery and
innovation.

01:03:06.630 --> 01:03:10.540
This is precisely where CMU excels.

01:03:10.540 --> 01:03:14.830
In fact,
we have cultivated distinct leadership

01:03:14.830 --> 01:03:19.450
where these two areas intersect at
the nexus of technology and society.

01:03:20.780 --> 01:03:28.020
Through this expertise, we're enhancing
the way we live, work and communicate

01:03:28.020 --> 01:03:34.020
and we're shaping modern culture through
visionary art, performance and design.

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:41.540
CMU legend Herb Simon once said,
we're not observers of the future,

01:03:42.540 --> 01:03:46.820
we're actors,
our job is to design a sustainable and

01:03:46.820 --> 01:03:50.080
acceptable world and bring it about.

01:03:51.530 --> 01:03:58.480
This remains true, as true today as when
he said it more than 20 years ago.

01:04:00.450 --> 01:04:05.800
What has also remained constant is
the tremendous responsibility that comes

01:04:05.800 --> 01:04:06.930
with this influence.

01:04:08.160 --> 01:04:12.970
I was reminded of this last year when I
came across an editorial by David Brooks

01:04:12.970 --> 01:04:18.140
in the New York Times, which
reflected on Pittsburgh's Renaissance.

01:04:18.140 --> 01:04:23.480
Of course, our connection to this
city is one of our greatest strengths.

01:04:25.040 --> 01:04:30.640
But this article,
while acknowledging CMU's positive impact,

01:04:30.640 --> 01:04:36.440
also warned of a so-called,
Carnegie Mellon layer of prosperity.

01:04:38.320 --> 01:04:42.840
That had not quite penetrated
working class neighborhoods.

01:04:42.840 --> 01:04:46.310
Indeed, we are witnessing
the disenfranchisement

01:04:46.310 --> 01:04:49.330
of a growing segment of our population,

01:04:49.330 --> 01:04:53.480
people who just do not see themselves
as part of this new economy,

01:04:54.790 --> 01:04:57.390
who can't even imagine a pathway to entry.

01:04:59.300 --> 01:05:05.111
While the nature of this divide has
been debated by pundits on the left and

01:05:05.111 --> 01:05:10.310
on the right, this goes far beyond partisan politics.

01:05:10.310 --> 01:05:12.330
We all bear responsibility for

01:05:12.330 --> 01:05:17.060
ensuring that the future we
are building works for everyone.

01:05:17.060 --> 01:05:22.561
If we succeed, the United States
will continue to serve as a shining

01:05:22.561 --> 01:05:27.781
example of prosperity and
democracy for the rest of the world.

01:05:27.781 --> 01:05:30.891
Here lies the greatest obligation for

01:05:30.891 --> 01:05:35.172
institutions of higher
learning in the modern era

01:05:35.172 --> 01:05:40.751
and a commitment that lies at
the heart of CMU's leadership.

01:05:40.751 --> 01:05:45.712
Even as we break new ground in technology,
we must work to mitigate

01:05:45.712 --> 01:05:50.600
any consequences that diminish
human dignity and opportunity.

01:05:51.740 --> 01:05:58.338
That is why at CMU, scientists and
engineers work together with philosophers,

01:05:58.338 --> 01:06:03.392
artists, economists who will
shape what might be possible,

01:06:03.392 --> 01:06:08.380
with ethicists, humanists, and
policy experts, who will guide our path

01:06:10.340 --> 01:06:15.230
and with the behavioral scientists
who will measure the impact of our

01:06:15.230 --> 01:06:16.614
work on humanity.

01:06:16.614 --> 01:06:22.350
Reinforcing our distinct strength at
the nexus of technology and humanity will

01:06:22.350 --> 01:06:28.440
be crucial to building an extraordinary
momentum in both research and creativity.

01:06:29.510 --> 01:06:34.300
And as president, I am committed
to supporting this leadership.

01:06:34.300 --> 01:06:38.344
By investing in a diverse community
of faculty and researchers,

01:06:38.344 --> 01:06:42.688
by doubling down on our partnership
beyond the borders of our campus

01:06:42.688 --> 01:06:47.258
and by creating vibrant living
laboratories in communities around

01:06:47.258 --> 01:06:48.066
the world.

01:06:48.066 --> 01:06:51.526
This is the next frontier for
Carnegie Mellon and

01:06:51.526 --> 01:06:56.600
I believe it will only deepen our
societal impact heading into the future.

01:06:56.600 --> 01:07:06.600
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:07:07.880 --> 01:07:12.500
&gt;&gt; As much as we value the impact of our

01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:18.410
research and creativity, we are equally
committed to our educational mission

01:07:19.490 --> 01:07:21.430
and as a CMU parent,

01:07:21.430 --> 01:07:26.840
the responsibility of preparing the next
generation is deeply personal to me.

01:07:28.935 --> 01:07:34.097
For the CMU students, here today,

01:07:34.097 --> 01:07:39.720
and also across various campuses and
on our campus watch parties,

01:07:42.390 --> 01:07:45.130
you are my most important motivation.

01:07:47.820 --> 01:07:51.300
You're spending your
most formative years here

01:07:51.300 --> 01:07:54.320
from what I remember from
my own college experience.

01:07:55.660 --> 01:07:59.517
You are undoubtably forming
life-long friendships.

01:07:59.517 --> 01:08:03.020
You know, many of my best friends from college
are still my best friends today.

01:08:04.740 --> 01:08:09.590
The foundation you built here will
sustain you as you enter a world defined

01:08:09.590 --> 01:08:11.800
by continuous disruption.

01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:15.790
According to a recent study, about two
thirds of jobs that you will

01:08:15.790 --> 01:08:19.069
hold throughout your
lives do not even exist.

01:08:20.720 --> 01:08:23.890
This reality has dramatic and
immediate implications for

01:08:23.890 --> 01:08:26.060
the kind of education you deserve today.

01:08:27.710 --> 01:08:33.450
Throughout our history, every period
of significant technological change

01:08:33.450 --> 01:08:37.820
has been met with a corresponding
wave of innovation in education.

01:08:39.770 --> 01:08:43.720
I'm here to tell you, that right now,

01:08:43.720 --> 01:08:50.080
we are at the dawn of the next major
transformation in education

01:08:50.080 --> 01:08:54.283
and Carnegie Mellon will be at
the forefront of these changes.

01:08:54.283 --> 01:08:58.607
From curriculum to pedagogy,
to structure and organization,

01:08:58.607 --> 01:09:02.700
we are re-imagining our education
with your futures in mind.

01:09:04.450 --> 01:09:08.080
We're breaking down disciplinary silos and
launching

01:09:08.080 --> 01:09:12.696
cross-cutting programs that better serve
your interests and societies' needs.

01:09:12.696 --> 01:09:18.820
Programs like behavioral economics,
neuroscience and IDEATE.

01:09:18.820 --> 01:09:23.578
We're embedding continuous learning
in the skills that will only increase

01:09:23.578 --> 01:09:27.770
in demand as automation
reshapes the future work.

01:09:27.770 --> 01:09:32.000
Skills like communication,
critical thinking and entrepreneurship.

01:09:33.400 --> 01:09:38.710
We're investing in infrastructure that
supports the new ways that students learn

01:09:38.710 --> 01:09:42.832
and collaborate,
spaces like Tepper Quad and Scott Hall.

01:09:42.832 --> 01:09:47.583
We are utilizing our
expertise in the science of

01:09:47.583 --> 01:09:51.978
learning to develop
a personalized model of

01:09:51.978 --> 01:09:56.982
education focused on how
each of you learns best.

01:09:56.982 --> 01:10:02.034
Every day we work to build and
sustain a community that's inclusive,

01:10:02.034 --> 01:10:07.270
equitable, nurturing for
both graduate and undergraduate students.

01:10:07.270 --> 01:10:12.034
A place where diverse perspectives
can come together in a culture of

01:10:12.034 --> 01:10:13.380
civil discourse.

01:10:14.860 --> 01:10:18.530
To our students, thank you for

01:10:18.530 --> 01:10:23.910
entrusting us with this most
important chapter in your lives.

01:10:25.700 --> 01:10:32.656
You will always be at
the heart of my presidency.

01:10:32.656 --> 01:10:33.883
As we consider-

01:10:33.883 --> 01:10:43.326
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:10:43.326 --> 01:10:45.982
&gt;&gt; As we consider aspirations that unite

01:10:45.982 --> 01:10:50.796
this global community,
philanthropy must continue to catalyze and

01:10:50.796 --> 01:10:53.040
support our forward momentum.

01:10:54.220 --> 01:10:58.690
In fact, this university was
founded by an act of philanthropy.

01:11:00.150 --> 01:11:05.850
At this pivotal moment, I am delighted
today to announce two extraordinary

01:11:05.850 --> 01:11:10.110
new commitments that will provide
critical resources to Carnegie Mellon.

01:11:11.270 --> 01:11:16.110
In recent years, Carnegie Mellon has
been making significant investments for

01:11:16.110 --> 01:11:17.790
our College of Engineering,

01:11:17.790 --> 01:11:23.280
including a state of the art maker
ecosystem that serves the entire campus.

01:11:23.280 --> 01:11:27.824
Today I'm pleased to announce that
the Allegheny Foundation has committed

01:11:27.824 --> 01:11:31.658
a $30 million lead grant toward
the transformation of Scaife

01:11:31.658 --> 01:11:36.000
Hall into a modern new home for
our Mechanical Engineering Department.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:46.000
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:11:52.302 --> 01:11:54.666
&gt;&gt; This grant, the largest in the history

01:11:54.666 --> 01:12:00.040
of Allegheny Foundation, will enable us to
bring our total infrastructure investments

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:04.960
in engineering over the last decade to
more than a quarter billion dollars.

01:12:04.960 --> 01:12:10.870
But this commitment, CMU will be better
able to compete for best students and

01:12:10.870 --> 01:12:16.330
faculty, driving Pittsburgh's
reputation as a hub for innovation.

01:12:16.330 --> 01:12:19.720
We're joined today by Matt Groll,
President and

01:12:19.720 --> 01:12:21.780
Chairman of Allegheny Foundation.

01:12:21.780 --> 01:12:24.315
Please join me in thanking
Allegheny Foundation for

01:12:24.315 --> 01:12:26.222
their generosity to Carnegie Mellon.

01:12:26.222 --> 01:12:28.607
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Matt, please stand to be recognized.

01:12:28.607 --> 01:12:38.607
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:12:40.723 --> 01:12:43.783
&gt;&gt; At a time when college education has

01:12:43.783 --> 01:12:48.883
never been more important,
many prospective students and

01:12:48.883 --> 01:12:53.473
middle class families feel
as though they're simply

01:12:53.473 --> 01:12:58.484
priced out of education that
they may need for the future.

01:12:58.484 --> 01:13:04.491
This is why CMU has made growing our
endowment for scholarship, fellowships,

01:13:04.491 --> 01:13:09.792
and financial aid, one of our most
important strategic priorities.

01:13:09.792 --> 01:13:15.887
Today I am pleased to announce
that CMU trustee Todd Johnson and

01:13:15.887 --> 01:13:22.672
his wife Cindy have committed $50
million to create an endowment to

01:13:22.672 --> 01:13:28.423
support undergraduate scholarship and
student success.

01:13:28.423 --> 01:13:38.423
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:14:00.181 --> 01:14:01.442
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]

01:14:01.442 --> 01:14:11.442
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:14:18.235 --> 01:14:20.708
&gt;&gt; You know, I made the announcement a couple of

01:14:20.708 --> 01:14:24.041
times yesterday, and
I said this last night.

01:14:24.041 --> 01:14:29.352
Every time I'm making this announcement
when I get to the word student,

01:14:29.352 --> 01:14:30.230
I choke up.

01:14:31.840 --> 01:14:32.708
That's why we're here.

01:14:32.708 --> 01:14:36.705
Todd and Cindy will you stand
please to be recognized.

01:14:36.705 --> 01:14:41.404
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:14:41.404 --> 01:14:52.216
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:14:52.216 --> 01:14:53.280
&gt;&gt; Well, I lost my place.

01:14:53.280 --> 01:14:54.929
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]

01:15:02.823 --> 01:15:04.920
Boy, I didn't realize this
speech was this long.

01:15:04.920 --> 01:15:10.068
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; I know, tell me about it.

01:15:13.122 --> 01:15:18.527
Well,
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]

01:15:23.065 --> 01:15:25.257
&gt;&gt; Back to the place that I lost track

01:15:25.257 --> 01:15:25.898
of time.

01:15:25.898 --> 01:15:30.708
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; This support will greatly expand our

01:15:30.708 --> 01:15:35.000
ability to ensure that
a Carnegie Mellon education

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:38.908
is within the reach of
all talented students.

01:15:41.414 --> 01:15:47.717
This gift, the largest toward scholarship
support in Carnegie Mellon's history,

01:15:47.717 --> 01:15:51.917
was inspired by Todd's own path
to success here at CMU and

01:15:51.917 --> 01:15:55.260
the fellowships that funded his education.

01:15:57.160 --> 01:16:00.470
Please once again join me in thanking and

01:16:00.470 --> 01:16:05.215
congratulating the Johnsons for their
generosity and commitment to our students.

01:16:05.215 --> 01:16:08.405
Todd and Cindy, we are so
grateful to you for your generosity.

01:16:08.405 --> 01:16:16.458
[APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:16:16.458 --> 01:16:22.210
&gt;&gt; I hope you packed a good lunch.

01:16:22.210 --> 01:16:22.718
This is a long speech.

01:16:22.718 --> 01:16:27.640
My fellow Tartans.

01:16:27.640 --> 01:16:32.233
Whether you're in Pittsburgh,
Silicon Valley,

01:16:32.233 --> 01:16:37.249
Australia, Rwanda or Qatar,
I hope you are as excited as

01:16:37.249 --> 01:16:42.080
I am about the future of
Carnegie Mellon University.

01:16:43.850 --> 01:16:48.360
To be part of CMU at
this moment is to be at

01:16:48.360 --> 01:16:53.560
the cusp of the next great phase of
societal and human development.

01:16:55.250 --> 01:17:01.930
If we continue doing what we do today,
we'll maintain momentum and

01:17:01.930 --> 01:17:06.100
continue to be a great university.

01:17:06.100 --> 01:17:10.680
But if we are very intentional, if we

01:17:10.680 --> 01:17:17.600
are unapologetically bold, and
if we are committed to taking risks.

01:17:19.040 --> 01:17:22.620
I am confident that we
will position ourselves

01:17:22.620 --> 01:17:25.338
among the top tier
institutions in the world.

01:17:25.338 --> 01:17:31.155
A place that's known for writing the story of this century.

01:17:31.155 --> 01:17:35.960
An institution dedicated
to anticipating and

01:17:35.960 --> 01:17:40.390
solving the most pressing
challenges facing humanity.

01:17:40.390 --> 01:17:45.940
Through creative inquiry, through
scientific discovery, through the impact

01:17:45.940 --> 01:17:51.370
of technology and through a transformative
education that changes lives.

01:17:52.700 --> 01:17:58.290
As we embark on this exhilarating
future together, we do so

01:17:58.290 --> 01:18:03.665
as a community bound together
by a set of core values

01:18:03.665 --> 01:18:05.706
that serve as our foundation.

01:18:05.706 --> 01:18:12.850
Integrity, knowledge, compassion, respect.

01:18:12.850 --> 01:18:17.940
The great scientist Albert Einstein
understood this fundamental connection

01:18:17.940 --> 01:18:20.650
between excellence and human values.

01:18:21.900 --> 01:18:23.440
In 1950 he wrote,

01:18:24.800 --> 01:18:30.150
only morality in our actions can
give beauty and dignity to life.

01:18:32.020 --> 01:18:37.199
To make this a living force and
bring it to clear consciousness

01:18:38.280 --> 01:18:42.340
is perhaps the foremost task of education.

01:18:44.670 --> 01:18:48.080
Andrew Carnegie put it
a little more simply.

01:18:49.130 --> 01:18:50.540
My heart is in the work.

01:18:52.030 --> 01:18:56.880
Each one of us has a role to
play in bringing beauty and

01:18:56.880 --> 01:18:58.890
dignity to our mission.

01:18:58.890 --> 01:19:02.868
Through the impact we make on society,
the leaders we develop and

01:19:02.868 --> 01:19:05.418
the opportunities we create for others.

01:19:05.418 --> 01:19:10.727
I feel privileged to work with
such outstanding partners and

01:19:10.727 --> 01:19:15.318
I look forward to all that
we will achieve together.

01:19:15.318 --> 01:19:16.842
Thank you very much.

01:19:16.842 --> 01:19:24.065
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:19:24.080 --> 01:19:53.360
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:19:54.720 --> 01:19:57.920
I hereby declare this inauguration of the tenth president

01:19:57.920 --> 01:19:59.920
of Carnegie Mellon University to be concluded.

01:20:00.160 --> 01:20:04.195
The audience is requested to remain
at your seats until the completion

01:20:04.195 --> 01:20:05.640
of the recession.

01:20:05.640 --> 01:20:08.415
And now please rise for
the singing of the Alma Mater,

01:20:08.415 --> 01:20:11.140
which will be sung by members
of The School of Music.

01:20:29.600 --> 01:21:31.760
[MUSIC]

01:21:34.080 --> 01:21:42.462
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

01:21:42.480 --> 01:23:15.840
